\noindent \textbf{Question 1} (100 points)\medskip

\setcounter{section}{1}

\noindent We study the decision problem of an infinitely lived firm that needs to hire
one worker to produce output. At the beginning of each period, a firm that
wants to engage in hiring must pay a search cost $c\geq 0$ and then randomly
meets a worker who is characterized by his productivity $a$. Productivity is
drawn from a distribution with cdf $F\left( a\right) $, and it is a fixed
characteristic of the worker. $F\left( a\right) $ is is continuous with
bounded support $\left[ 0,\bar{a}\right] $, with $\bar{a}>c$.\ If employed,
the worker produces output $y=a$.

If the firm decides to hire the worker, he immediately starts working, and
the firm leaves the search market. The firm pays the worker a wage $w\in
\left( 0,\bar{a}\right) $ in each period, irrespective of his productivity,
and keeps profit $y-w$. The firm discounts profits at rate $\beta \in \left(
0,1\right) $. After each period of employment, the worker may randomly
separate from the firm---he stays with probability $\rho \in \left[ 0,1%
\right] $ and leaves with probability $1-\rho $. If the worker leaves, the
firm terminates its operation.

If the firm decides not to hire the worker, it has to wait until the next
period, pay the search cost again and repeat the process.

\begin{question}
\textbf{[5 points]} Denote $V\left( a\right) $ the value of a firm that met
a worker with productivity $a$. Formulate the Bellman equation for the value
of the firm.

\begin{answer}
Assuming that the firm wants to continue searching in the next period, we
have%
\begin{equation*}
V\left( a\right) =\max_{\left\{ \text{accept, reject}\right\} }\left\{
\sum_{t=0}^{\infty }\left( \beta \rho \right) ^{t}\left( a-w\right) ,-\beta
c+\beta \int_{0}^{\bar{a}}V\left( a^{\prime }\right) dF\left( a^{\prime
}\right) \right\} .
\end{equation*}
\end{answer}
\end{question}

\begin{question}
\textbf{[5 points]} Prove that the optimal decision of the firm is
characterized by a cutoff rule.

\begin{answer}
Again, assuming that the worker wants to search, we can rewrite the Bellman
equation as%
\begin{equation*}
V\left( a\right) =\max_{\left\{ \text{accept, reject}\right\} }\left\{ \frac{%
a-w}{1-\beta \rho },-\beta c+\beta \int_{0}^{\bar{a}}V\left( a^{\prime
}\right) dF\left( a^{\prime }\right) \right\} .
\end{equation*}%
Since the first term on the right-hand side is linearly increasing in $a$,
and the second is constant, there is a threshold $a^{\ast }$ such that if $%
a>a^{\ast }$ strictly prefers to hire the worker.
\end{answer}
\end{question}

\begin{question}
\textbf{[10 points]} If a firm decided to search for a worker in this period
and decided not to hire, will it want to search next period again? Prove
your answer.

\begin{answer}
The decision to engage in searching is given by the problem%
\begin{equation}
\bar{V}=\max_{\left\{ \text{search, not search}\right\} }\left\{
-c+\int_{0}^{\bar{a}}V\left( a\right) dF\left( a\right) ,0\right\}
\label{eq:Vbar_ex_ante_search}
\end{equation}%
where $\bar{V}$ is the value of the firm before it enters the search market
(it is the value of option to search). Since the terms on the right-hand
side are constant, the decision is time invariant.
\end{answer}
\end{question}

\begin{question}
\textbf{[20 points]} Characterize the threshold $\bar{c}$ for the search
cost such that firms stop searching for workers. How does the threshold $%
\bar{c}$ depend on the wage $w$ and on the discount rate parameter $\beta $?

\begin{answer}
We can now write the ex ante value of search as a function of the search
cost parameter, $\bar{V}\left( c\right) $. The first term in (\ref%
{eq:Vbar_ex_ante_search}) is decreasing in $c$, since both $-c$ and $V\left(
a\right) $ are decreasing in $c$, it is positive for $c=0$ and negative for
sufficiently high $c$. Therefore, there exists a $\bar{c}$ such that if $c>%
\bar{c}$, firms do not search, and search when $c<\bar{c}$.

Further, $V\left( a\right) $ (the value of a searching firm that met worker
with productivity $a$) is decreasing in $w$ and increasing in $\beta $. The
first term in (\ref{eq:Vbar_ex_ante_search}) is therefore decreasing in $w$
and increasing in $\beta $, and hence $\bar{c}$ is decreasing in $w$ and
increasing in $\beta $.
\end{answer}
\end{question}

\begin{question}
\textbf{[20 points]} Assume that there is a fixed unit mass of firms that
engage in search (i.e., firms that have been successful in the previous
period are replaced by new entrants in the search market). We can define the
labor demand curve in this model to be the relationship between the market
wage $w$ and the number of new workers hired by firms in a given period.
Show that the labor demand curve is decreasing in $w$.

\begin{answer}
The number of hired workers in each period depends on the productivity
cutoff and is given by $1-F\left( a^{\ast }\right) $. Hence we need to
establish the dependence of $a^{\ast }$ on $w$. Notice that we have%
\begin{equation*}
V\left( a\right) =\left\{
\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{a-w}{1-\beta \rho } & \text{if }a\geq a^{\ast } \\
V\left( a^{\ast }\right) =\frac{a^{\ast }-w}{1-\beta \rho } & \text{if }%
a\leq a^{\ast }%
\end{array}%
\right.
\end{equation*}%
The indifference condition that determines the cutoff is therefore given by%
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{a^{\ast }-w}{1-\beta \rho } &=&-\beta c+\beta \int_{0}^{\bar{a}%
}V\left( a^{\prime }\right) dF\left( a^{\prime }\right) =-\beta c+\beta
\int_{0}^{a^{\ast }}V\left( a^{\prime }\right) dF\left( a^{\prime }\right)
+\beta \int_{a^{\ast }}^{\bar{a}}V\left( a^{\prime }\right) dF\left(
a^{\prime }\right)  \\
&=&-\beta c+\beta \frac{a^{\ast }-w}{1-\beta \rho }+\beta \int_{a^{\ast }}^{%
\bar{a}}\left[ V\left( a^{\prime }\right) -V\left( a^{\ast }\right) \right]
dF\left( a^{\prime }\right)  \\
&=&-\beta c+\beta \frac{a^{\ast }-w}{1-\beta \rho }+\frac{\beta }{1-\beta
\rho }\int_{a^{\ast }}^{\bar{a}}\left[ a^{\prime }-a^{\ast }\right] dF\left(
a^{\prime }\right)
\end{eqnarray*}%
and hence%
\begin{equation*}
\frac{1-\beta }{1-\beta \rho }\left( a^{\ast }-w\right) +\beta c=\frac{\beta
}{1-\beta \rho }\int_{a^{\ast }}^{\bar{a}}\left[ a^{\prime }-a^{\ast }\right]
dF\left( a^{\prime }\right) .
\end{equation*}%
The left-hand side, as a function of $a^{\ast }$ is linearly increasing and
starts negative at zero. The right-hand side is strictly decreasing, starts
positive and ends at zero at $a^{\ast }=\bar{a}$. Hence the two curves
intersect exactly once, determining the cutoff point $\bar{w}$. Moreover, an
increase in $w$ shifts the curve on the left-hand side down, hence
increasing the cutoff productivity level $a^{\ast }$. Hence a higher $w$
leads to a (strict) decrease in the number of hired workers $1-F\left(
a^{\ast }\right) $, and the labor demand curve is decreasing.
\end{answer}
\end{question}

\begin{question}
\textbf{[20 points]} Imagine that at time $t=0$, the economy starts with
zero employed workers. Denote $e_{t}$ the number of workers who work in
period $t$. Formulate the law of motion for employment $e_{t}$ in this
economy. How does $e_{t}$ behave as $t\rightarrow \infty $?

\begin{answer}
We have%
\begin{equation*}
e_{t+1}=\rho e_{t}+\left( 1-F\left( a^{\ast }\right) \right)
\end{equation*}%
where $\rho $ is the staying rate. Since $1-F\left( a^{\ast }\right) $ is a
constant, $e_{t}$ will converge to the limit%
\begin{equation*}
\bar{e}=\lim_{t\rightarrow \infty }e_{t}=\frac{1-F\left( a^{\ast }\right) }{%
1-\rho }\text{.}
\end{equation*}%
The rate of convergence is determined by%
\begin{eqnarray*}
e_{t+1}-\bar{e} &=&\rho \left( e_{t}-\bar{e}\right) +\left( 1-F\left(
a^{\ast }\right) \right) -\left( 1-\rho \right) \bar{e} \\
&=&\rho \left( e_{t}-\bar{e}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}%
and hence the rate of convergence is $\rho $.
\end{answer}
\end{question}

\begin{question}
\textbf{[20 points]} Consider an alternative economy in which the government
taxes profits $y-w$ at rate $\tau \in \left[ 0,1\right] $ (and firms cannot
deduct search cost as an expense). Imagine both economies start with zero
employment at time $t=0$. Compare their employment levels at a given time $t$%
.

\begin{answer}
Assume for now that the tax rate is sufficiently low such that firms are
willing to pay the search cost. Denote $a_{\tau }^{\ast }$ the cutoff for
the productivity level when the tax rate is $\tau $ and $V_{\tau }$ the
associated value function. Then the cutoff is determined by the indifference
condition%
\begin{equation*}
\frac{\left( 1-\tau \right) \left( a^{\ast }-w\right) }{1-\beta \rho }%
=-\beta c+\beta \int_{0}^{\bar{a}}V_{\tau }\left( a^{\prime }\right)
dF\left( a^{\prime }\right) .
\end{equation*}%
Further, we have%
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\left( 1-\tau \right) \left( a^{\ast }-w\right) }{1-\beta \rho }
&=&-\beta c+\beta \int_{0}^{a_{\tau }^{\ast }}V_{\tau }\left( a^{\prime
}\right) dF\left( a^{\prime }\right) +\beta \int_{a_{\tau }^{\ast }}^{\bar{a}%
}V_{\tau }\left( a^{\prime }\right) dF\left( a^{\prime }\right)  \\
&=&-\beta c+\beta \frac{\left( 1-\tau \right) \left( a^{\ast }-w\right) }{%
1-\beta \rho }+\beta \int_{a_{\tau }^{\ast }}^{\bar{a}}\left[ V_{\tau
}\left( a^{\prime }\right) -V_{\tau }\left( a^{\ast }\right) \right]
dF\left( a^{\prime }\right)  \\
&=&-\beta c+\beta \frac{\left( 1-\tau \right) \left( a^{\ast }-w\right) }{%
1-\beta \rho }+\beta \frac{1-\tau }{1-\beta \rho }\int_{a_{\tau }^{\ast }}^{%
\bar{a}}\left[ a^{\prime }-a_{\tau }^{\ast }\right] dF\left( a^{\prime
}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}%
and hence%
\begin{equation*}
\frac{\left( 1-\beta \right) \left( a^{\ast }-w\right) }{1-\beta \rho }+%
\frac{\beta c}{1-\tau }=\frac{\beta }{1-\beta \rho }\int_{a_{\tau }^{\ast
}}^{\bar{a}}\left[ a^{\prime }-a_{\tau }^{\ast }\right] dF\left( a^{\prime
}\right)
\end{equation*}%
Repeating the argument from a previous exercise, treating both sides as
functions of $a_{\tau }^{\ast }$, an increase in $\tau $ shifts the function
on the left-hand side upward, and hence the intersect (optimal $a_{\tau
}^{\ast }$) decreases. As a consequence, the number of employed workers $%
1-F\left( a_{\tau }^{\ast }\right) $ increases, as firms become less
selective and reject less workers. The reason is that with the tax, search
costs are relatively higher compared to after tax profits, so firms want to
avoid paying the cost repeatedly (the option value of waiting is lower). In
such an economy with tax, employment $e_{t}$ will be higher at any given
time $t$ compared to an economy without tax.

However, when the tax increases so much that firms find it optimal not to
search,%
\begin{equation*}
\bar{V}_{\tau }=\max_{\left\{ \text{search, not search}\right\} }\left\{
-c+\int_{0}^{\bar{a}}V_{\tau }\left( a\right) dF\left( a\right) ,0\right\}
\end{equation*}
(see equation (\ref{eq:Vbar_ex_ante_search})), then employment in the
economy with tax remains at zero forever.
\end{answer}
\end{question}



