\noindent \textbf{Question 3} (100 points)\medskip

\noindent\ Two notable trends in the macro data are a declining labor share
of income and a declining real interest rate. Analyze this issue in the
context of the following model..

\qquad Households preferences:

\begin{center}
$E_{0}\left\{ \sum_{t=0}^{\infty }\beta ^{t}\left[ \log C_{t+i}-\frac{1}{%
1+\varphi }L_{t+i}^{1+\varphi }\right] \right\} $
\end{center}

\qquad Budget constraint:

\begin{center}
$C_{t}=w_{t}L_{t}+\Pi _{t}-\frac{\left( \frac{1}{R_{t+1}}\right)
B_{t+1}-B_{t}}{P_{t}}$
\end{center}

\qquad Final goods output

\begin{center}
$Y_{t}=\left[ \int_{0}^{1}Y_{t}\left( f\right) ^{\frac{\varepsilon _{t}-1}{%
\varepsilon _{t}}}df\right] ^{\frac{\varepsilon _{t}}{\varepsilon _{t}-1}}$
\end{center}

\qquad Intermediate goods output

\begin{center}
$Y_{t}\left( f\right) =A L_{t}(f)$
\end{center}

\qquad First order condition for labor demand

\begin{center}
$A=(1+\mu _{t})w_{t}$
\end{center}

\qquad Markup (under flexible prices)

\begin{center}
$\frac{1}{1-1/\varepsilon _{t}}=1+\mu _{t}$
\end{center}

\qquad Resource constraint

\begin{center}
$Y_{t}=C_{t}$
\end{center}

\qquad Zero net supply of bonds in equilibrium

\begin{center}
$B_{t}=0$
\end{center}

with $0<\beta <1,$ $\varepsilon >1$ and $\varphi >0.$

i. \ \ What are the household's first order conditions for
consumption/saving and for labor supply?. Also, briefly, what is the
intuition for the intermediate goods producer's first order condition for
labor.?\bigskip

ii. \ Given i, collapse the flexible price model into three equations for $Y$
, $L_{t}$ and $R_{t+1}$(Assume a symmetric equilibrium:\ i.e. $Y_{t}\left(
f\right) =Y_{t}$ and $L_{t}(f)=L_{t}$)$.$\bigskip

iii. Now solve for the steady state values of $Y$ , $L_{t}$ and $R_{t+1}$,
given $\varepsilon $ is the steady state value of $\varepsilon _{t}.$ Also
find the steady state value of the wage $w$ and the labor share $wL/Y.$%
\bigskip

iv. Now suppose that the economy moves to a new steady state with a lower
labor share and a lower real interest rate. What primitive parameters of the
model need to change and how do they need to change in order to account for
the new steady state?


