\noindent \textbf{Question 4} (100 points)\medskip

\noindent Consider the following environment. Time is
discrete and the horizon infinite; every period is indexed by $t\in \mathbb{T%
}\equiv \left\{ 0,1,...\right\} $. There is a countably infinite number of
agent types, also indexed by $t\in \mathbb{T}$, and a large number (a unit
continuum) of agents of each type. There is a countably infinite number of
consumption goods, indexed by $s\in \mathbb{T}$. Let $c_{t}\left( s\right) $
denote the quantity of good $s$ consumed by agent of type $t$, and let $%
\boldsymbol{c}_{t}\equiv \left\{ c_{t}\left( s\right) \right\} _{s\in
\mathbb{T}}$. Each agent of type $t\in \mathbb{T}$, ranks consumption
bundles according to the following utility function
\begin{equation*}
U\left( \boldsymbol{c}_{t}\right) =c_{t}\left( t\right) +c_{t}\left(
t+1\right) .
\end{equation*}%
This is a pure-endowment economy. Let $\omega _{t}\left( s\right) $ denote
the quantity of good $s$ that an agent of type $t$ is endowed with, and let $%
\boldsymbol{\omega }_{t}\equiv \left\{ \omega _{t}\left( s\right) \right\}
_{s\in \mathbb{T}}$, with%
\begin{equation*}
\omega _{t}\left( s\right) =\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ t=s\right\} },
\end{equation*}%
where $\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ t=s\right\} }$ is an indicator function that
equals $1$ if $t=s$, and $0$ otherwise.

\begin{description}
\item[\textbf{(1)} ] [20 points] Define a competitive equilibrium with
Arrow-Debreu time-0 trading for this economy.

\item[\textbf{(2) }] [20 points] Prove that the prices $\left\{ p_{t}^{\ast
}\right\} _{t\in \mathbb{T}}$, with $p_{t}^{\ast }=1$ for all $t$, support
the allocation $\left\{ \boldsymbol{c}_{t}^{\ast }\right\} _{t\in \mathbb{T}%
}=\left\{ c_{t}^{\ast }\left( s\right) \right\} _{s,t\in \mathbb{T}}$, with $%
c_{t}^{\ast }\left( s\right) =\mathbb{I}_{\left\{ s=t\right\} }$ as a
competitive equilibrium.

\item[\textbf{(3)} ] [20 points] Define Pareto optimality in the context of
this particular environment.

\item[\textbf{(4) }] [40 points] Prove one of the following statements:

\begin{description}
\item[\textbf{(a)} ] The competitive equilibrium described in part (2) is
Pareto optimal.

\item[\textbf{(b) }] The competitive equilibrium described in part (2) is
not Pareto optimal.
\end{description}
\end{description}

